Based on the scenario provided, the patient has a pigmented macular lesion on the dorsum of his hand and the KOH examination revealed septated filaments. These features are highly suggestive of a superficial fungal infection. Tinea nigra, a superficial fungal infection caused by Hortaea werneckii, typically presents as a brown to black, well-demarcated patch frequently found on the palms (and can sometimes be seen on the dorsal aspects) and is more common in tropical regions. Given the history of recent relocation from coastal Mexico and the clinical findings, tinea nigra is the most likely diagnosis.

Answer: \boxed{A}

